analysis_text:
> DETAILS
This is a Marschak-Machina triangle. It represents all lotteries over three ordered outcomes as points inside a triangle, where the top corner corresponds to certainty of the best outcome and the right corner corresponds to certainty of the worst outcome. The position of a point reflects the probabilities assigned to these outcomes, with the probability of the remaining middle outcome determined implicitly so that all probabilities sum to one. Moving within the triangle changes probability mass across outcomes while keeping payoffs fixed, so the geometry represents probability tradeoffs rather than changes in outcomes. Indifference curves drawn over the triangle summarize preferences, with straight parallel lines characterizing expected utility and systematic curvature or fanning indicating violations of it.

The preferences in this triangle show clear departures from straight, parallel indifference curves, with a pronounced fanning-out pattern across the simplex. Near the left edge, the implied tradeoffs are very steep, indicating that introducing even a small probability of the worst outcome must be offset by a large increase in the probability of the best outcome to keep a lottery equally attractive. As the probability of the worst outcome rises, the model continues to demand increasingly strong compensation in terms of best-outcome probability, implying that downside risk carries disproportionate weight in evaluation. Overall, the pattern is consistent with strong downside aversion and nonlinear probability tradeoffs rather than near-linear expected-value reasoning.
tldr_text: The model really dislikes the chance of a bad outcomeif the bad outcome becomes more likely, it needs a much bigger chance of the best outcome to be willing to take the gamble.
